# Summary

<div class="block">

![Cyclic Group $\bbz_6$](/img/diagrams/abstract/cyclic-group.png)

If $G$ is a group and $a \in G$, then $H = \{ a^n : n \in \bbz \}$ is a subgroup of $G$. This group 
is the **cyclic subgroup $\lrangle{a}$ of $G$ generated by $a$**. Note that all subgroups containing
$a$ must contain every element in $\lrangle{a}$: it is the smallest group containing $a$. 
Given a group $G$ and an element $a$ in $G$, if $G = \{ a^n : n \in \bbz \}$, then $a$ is a **generator of $G$** 
and the group $G = \lrangle{a}$ is **cyclic**. If the subgroup $\lrangle{a}$ is finite, then the **order of $a$**
is the order $\left|\lrangle{a}\right|$ of this cyclic subgroup. Otherwise $a$ is of **infinite order**.

As an aside, cyclic groups are especially important in that they serve as the building blocks of all sufficiently small
abelian groups (in particular, finite abelian groups). That is, we can completely describe all finite abelian groups,
up to isomorphism, through the use of cyclic groups.

</div>

<div class="proof">

We can show that for some group $G$ and element $a \in G$, $H = \{ a^n : n \in \bbz \}$ is both a group and the smallest 
subgroup of $G$ containing $a$ simultaneously. First off, we note that all groups must be closed, so any subgroup containing 
$a$ must contain $a^n$ for some positive integer $n$. Since for every $a^r, a^s \in H$ we have $a^ra^s = a^{r+s}$, $H$ must
be closed. 
Since inverses must exist, we must also have $a^{-m}$ for all $m \in \bbz^+$. Then we note $a^{-m}a^m = e$ as desired. 
Lastly, every group must contain the identity element which is conveniently represented as $a^0$. Therefore a subgroup of 
$G$ containing $a$ must contain all elements $a^n$ (or $na$ for additive groups) for all $n \in \bbz$.

</div>

</section>

<section class="primary">

# Abelian Property

As alluded to in the summary, cyclic groups are the "building blocks" of all finite abelian groups. Thus we would expect
a cyclic group itself to be abelian. That does in fact hold.

<div class="proof">

Let $G$ by a cyclic group and let $a$ be a generator of $G$ so that $G = \lrangle{a} = \{a^n : n \in \bbz\}$.
If $g_1$ and $g_2$ are any two elements of $G$, there exist integers $r$ and $s$ such that $g_1 = a^r$ and 
$g_2 = a^s$. Then
$$ g_1g_2 = a^ra^s = a^{r+s} = a^{s+r} = a^sa^r = g_2g_1, $$
so $G$ is abelian.

</div>

</section>

<section class="primary">

# Structure

<div class="block">

![Isomorphic Cyclic Groups](/img/diagrams/abstract/isomorphic-cyclic-groups.png)

Let $G$ be a cyclic group with generator $a$. If the order of $G$ is infinite, then $G$ is isomorphic to
$\lrangle{\bbz, +}$. If $G$ has finite order $n$, then $G$ is isomorphic to $\lrangle{\bbz_n, +_n}$. Note
that we are claiming to be able to describe the structure of all cyclic groups in one fell swoop.

We also note the above is saying that there is only one infinite cyclic group up to isomorphism. Therefore
any group of infinite order that claims to be cyclic must have exactly two generators corresponding to
$1$ and $-1$.

</div>

<div class="proof">

Case I
:    Suppose the order of $G$ is infinite. Then for all positive integers $m$, $a^m \neq e$. In this case
     we claim that no two distinct exponents $h$ and $k$ can give equal elements $a^h$ and $a^k$ of $G$.
     Suppose that $a^h = a^k$ and say $h > k$. Then
     $$ a^ha^{-k} = a^{h-k} = e, $$
     contrary to the assumption that no $a^m = e$ for all $m \in \bbz^+$. Hence very element of $G$ can
     be expressed as $a^m$ for a unique $m \in \bbz$. The map $\phi: G \rightarrow \bbz$ given by
     $\phi(a^i) = i$ is thus well defined, one to one, and onto $\bbz$. Also,
     $$ \phi(a^ia^j) = \phi(a^{i+j}) = i + j = \phi(a^i) + \phi(a^j) $$
     so the homomorphism property is satisfied and $\phi$ is indeed an isomorphism.

<br />

Case II
:    Suppose $G$ has finite order. Then $a^m = e$ for some positive integer $m$. Let $n$ be the smallest
     positive integer such that $a^n = e$. If $s \in \bbz$ and $s = nq + r$ for $0 \leq r < n$, then
     $a^s = a^{nq + r} = \left(a^n\right)^qa^r = e^qa^r = a^r$. As in Case 1, if $0 < k < h < n$ and
     $a^h = a^k$, then $a^{h-k} = e$ and $0 < h - k < n$, contradicting our choice of $n$. Thus the elements
     $$ a^0 = e, a, a^2, a^3, \ldots, a^{n-1} $$
     are all distinct and comprise all elements of $G$. The map $\psi: G \rightarrow \bbz_n$ given by
     $\psi(a^i) = i$ for $i = 0, 1, 2, \ldots, n - 1$ is thus well defined, one to one, and onto $\bbz_n$.
     Because $a^n = e$, we see that $a^ia^j = a^k$ where $k = i +_n j$. Thus
     $$ \psi(a^ia^j) = i +_n j = \psi(a^i) +_n \psi(a^j), $$
     so the homomorphism property is satisfied and $\psi$ is an isomorphism.

</div>

</section>

