# Subgroups

<section class="secondary">

## Cyclicality

We note that the subgroup of every cyclic group must be cyclic. Note this is especially useful in classifying
infinite cyclic groups since an immediate consequence is the subgroups of $\bbz$ under addition must be precisely the
groups $n\bbz$ under addition for $n \in \bbz$.

<div class="proof">

Let $G$ be a cyclic group generated by $a$ and let $H$ be a subgroup of $G$. If $H = \{e\}$, then
$H = \lrangle{e}$ is cyclic. If $H \neq \{e\}$, then $a^n \in H$ for some $n \in \bbz^+$. Let $m$ be
the smallest integer in $\bbz^+$ such that $a^m \in H$ (it is the "smallest" element besides $e$ in $H$).
We claim that $c = a^m$ generates $H$; that is,
$$ H = \lrangle{a^m} = \lrangle{c}. $$
In order to prove this claim, we must show that every $b \in H$ is a power of $c$. Since $b \in H$ and
$H \leq G$, we have $b = a^n$ for some $n$. Then by the [division algorithm](division_algorithm) we can
find a $q$ and $r$ such that
$$ n = mq + r \quad\text{ for }\quad 0 \leq r < m. $$
Therefore $$ a^n = a^{mq + r} = \left(a^m\right)^q a^r, $$
so $$ a^r = \left( a^m \right)^{-q} a^n. $$
Since $H$ is a group and $a^n, a^m \in H$, then $a^r \in H$. Furthermore, since $m$ was the smallest positive
integer such that $a^m \in H$ and $0 \leq r < m$, we must have $r = 0$. Thus $n = qm$ and
$$ b = a^n = (a^m)^q = c^q, $$
so $b$ is a power of $c$.

</div>

</section>

<section class="secondary">

## Cardinality

Let $G$ be a cyclic group with $n$ elements and generated by $a$. Let $b \in G$ and let $b = a^s$. Then
$b$ generates a cyclic subgroup $H$ of $G$ containing $n/d$ elements, where $d$ is the greatest common
divisor of $n$ and $s$. Also, $\lrangle{a^s} = \lrangle{a^t}$ if and only if 
$\text{gcd}(s, n) = \text{gcd}(t, n)$. This immediately tells us the generators of a cyclic
group are those of form $a^r$ where $r$ is relatively prime to $n$.

<div class="proof">

That $b$ generates a cyclic subgroup is proven in the section labeled [cyclicality](#cyclicality). We need
show only that $H$ has $n/d$ elements. Noting that $H$ has as many elements as the smallest positive power
$m$ of $b$ that gives the identity, $b = a^s$ and $b^m = e$ if and only if $(a^s)^m = e$, or if and only
if $n$ divides $ms$. Since we want to find the smallest positive integer of $m$ such that $n$ divides $ms$, we
let $d$ be the gcd of $n$ and $s$. Then there exists integers $u$ and $v$ such that
$$ d = un + vs. $$
Since $d$ divides both $n$ and $s$, we may write
$$ 1 = u(n/d) + v(s/d) $$
where both $n/d$ and $s/d$ are integers. This last equation shows that $n/d$ and $s/d$ are relatively
prime, for any integer dividing both of them must also divide $1$. We wish to find the smallest positive
$m$ such that
$$ \frac{ms}{n} = \frac{m(s/d)}{(n/d)} \text{ is an integer}. $$
But by [prime relativity](greatest_common_divisor#prime-relativity), we conclude that $n/d$ must divide $m$,
so the smallest such $m$ is $n/d$. Thus the order of $H$ is $n/d$.

Now, taking $\bbz_n$ as a model for a cyclic group of order $n$, we see that if $d$ is a divisor of $n$,
then the cyclic subgroup $\lrangle{d}$ of $\bbz^n$ has $n/d$ elements, and contains all the positive integers
$m$ less than $n$ such that $\text{gcd}(m, n) = d$ (note this does not mean that every element in the group
has this gcd; rather, this states that those who share this gcd must also be in the group). Thus there is only one 
subgroup of $\bbz^n$ of order $n/d$, since all elements which have order $n/d$ are in all the other groups generated
by an element with order $n/d$. Taken with the preceding paragraph, this shows at once that if $a$ is a generator of 
the cyclic group $G$, then $\lrangle{a^s} = \lrangle{a^t}$ if and only if $\text{gcd}(s, n) = \text{gcd}(t, n)$.

</div>

